Partitions and partition tables.

A partition is a contiguous slice of a disk with its own boundaries. Why partition a disk at all? To hold several separate filesystems on one disk, perhaps one for the root and one for home directories; to reserve space for swap or recovery; to dual-boot more than one operating system; and because smaller filesystems are quicker to check for errors.

The partitions on a disk are described by a partition table at the very start of it, and there are two formats. The older standard is the master boot record, often shortened to m-b-r. It allows up to four primary partitions, caps the disk size at two terabytes, and holds the legacy boot code. It is still everywhere on older systems. The modern standard is the g-u-i-d partition table, or g-p-t. It allows up to a hundred and twenty-eight partitions by default, has essentially no size limit, keeps a backup copy of the table at the end of the disk for safety, and is required by the modern u-e-f-i firmware found on current machines. The advice is simple: use g-p-t for any new disk unless you have a specific reason not to.

You can check which format a disk uses, and edit its partitions, with a couple of tools. F-disk is the classic interactive tool; you press p to print the table, n to make a new partition, d to delete one, t to change a partition's type, and w to write your changes and exit, or q to quit without saving. Par-ted is newer, handles both formats, and crucially has a non-interactive command form that you can script, which makes it the usual choice for g-p-t work. There are also friendlier variants like g-disk and the menu-driven c-f-disk. And one warning hangs over all of them: any partition change can destroy data, so always back up first.
